The Texas Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices (Texas MUTCD, 2011 Edition) defines nine (9)
warrants, or justifying set of conditions, at least one of which should be fully satisfied before signalization
is considered as an option for traffic control. Factors included in the evaluation of these warrants include
vehicle and pedestrian traffic volumes, the number of traffic lanes, the prevailing traffic speeds, traffic
crash history, and measured delay for minor street traffic. The individual warrants are listed below,
followed by a short description of each.

The 2011 Edition of the TMUTCD contains nine warrants for traffic signals. The intersection currently
meets three of the five applicable warrants. Based on the criteria, a traffic signal is warranted at this time
for the intersection of Williams Drive and Jim Hogg Road.
An operational analysis was performed to determine the effect of adding lanes to change the existing
geometry of the intersection. Currently Jim Hogg has a shared left-through lane and a right turn lane
going northbound and a shared left-through-right southbound as seen on Figure 3. Three design
alternatives were considered for intersection improvement.
The first alternative involved creating an additional lane on Jim Hogg, creating a southbound left turn
pocket for traffic exiting the new City Service Center. Analysis showed that this lane does not
substantially improved intersection operations. Left turn movements on Jim Hogg are light enough that
they can be served out of the shared lane. Furthermore, a protected left turn arrow for Jim Hogg traffic is
not required and all side street movements can be accommodated by a three section signal head.
Protected left turns off of the side street are not required.

The second alternative considered was the potential construction of an acceleration lane for northbound
Jim Hogg traffic turning on to Williams Drive. The east leg of the intersection currently has an eight foot
wide enough shoulder. By adding an additional four feet of pavement to the shoulder, the acceleration
lane can be created for the northbound right turn movement, reducing the amount of green time needed
for the side street. This alternative will result in improved operations at the intersection and is
The third alternative studied was the treatment of left turns off of Williams Drive onto Jim Hogg. The
westbound left turn lane has substantial traffic during peak demand periods and would warrant a
protected left turn. Eastbound left turn traffic is light for most of the day. For this type of condition, a
protected-permissive left turn operation is recommended. This type of operation involves the use of a
“permissive left” flashing yellow arrow for the westbound left turn, followed by an actuated “protected left”
green arrow. Turning movements would only receive their arrow if they were delayed for a substantial
amount of time due to a lack of gaps in oncoming traffic. .
